quest_title: Rusting of iron is due to formation of
explanation_txt:
Final product of rusting gives hydrated ferric oxide.

The series of reaction is given as

Reduction of Oxygen

\(\mathrm{O}_{2}+4 \mathrm{e}^{-}+2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 4 \mathrm{OH}^{-}\)

Oxidation of iron

\(\mathrm{Fe} \rightarrow \mathrm{Fe}^{2+}+2 \mathrm{e}^{-}\)

Overall Redox reaction

\(4 \mathrm{Fe}^{2+}+\mathrm{O}_{2} \rightarrow 4 \mathrm{Fe}^{3+}+2 \mathrm{O}^{2-}\)

Acid-Base Reactions

\(\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}+2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{OH})_{2}+2 \mathrm{H}^{+}\)

\(\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{OH})_{3}+3 \mathrm{H}^{+}\)

Dehydration equilibrium

\(\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{OH})_{2} \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{FeO}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\)

\(\mathrm{Fe}(\mathrm{OH})_{3} \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{FeO}(\mathrm{OH})+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\)

\(2 \mathrm{FeO}(\mathrm{OH}) \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{Fe}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}.\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\) [Hydrated ferric oxide]

quest_title: A body of mass 4 kg moving with velocity 12 m/s collides with another body of mass 6 kg at rest. If two bodies stick together after collision, then the loss of kinetic energy of system is
explanation_txt:
Given,

\(m_1 = 4kg \\ u_1 = 12m/s \\ m_2 = 6kg \\ u_2 = 0 m/s \)

Conservation of momentum yields,

\(m_1u_1 + m_2u_2 = (m_1+m_2)V \\ \Rightarrow 48 = 10 \times V \\ \Rightarrow V = 4.8 m/s\)

Loss in energy is:

\(\begin{align} \Delta KE &= \cfrac{1}{2} \left( (m_1+m_2)V^2 - m_1u_1^2 \right) \\ &= \cfrac{1}{2} (10 \times 4.8^2 - 4 \times 12^2) \\ &= 172.8 J \end{align} \)

quest_title: 100 coplanar forces each equal to 10 N act on a body. Each force makes angle \(\cfrac{\pi}{50}\) with the preceding force. What is the resultant of the forces?
explanation_txt:
Given, angle between the vectors\(=\cfrac{\pi}{50}=\) Exterior angle of polygon formed arranging the forces sequentially.

Total sum of exterior angles \(= 100*\cfrac{\pi}{50}=2\pi\)

Therefore, the forces will form a closed 100-gon structure if positioned sequentially. For a closed geometry of vectors, their sum is zero. Thus, the resultant force is zero.
